 Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Halstad","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads, notably in southeastern Norway, so named from the Old Norse personal name <i>Hǫrthr</i> (someone from Hǫrthaland) or <i>Hárekr</i> (from <i>Há</i>, which is unexplained, + <i>rekr</i> ‘powerful, ruler’) + <i>stathr</i> ‘farmstead, dwelling’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecilia De Halstad was born in 1210, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, her father, Robert De Halstad, was 25 and her mother, Mrs. Robert Halstad, was 25. She had at least 4 sons with Sir William Talmache. She died in 1281, in her hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1210–1281":"1210–1281","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1198":"1198","1185":"1185","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1281":"1281","1349":"1349","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1224":"1224","about 1237":"umbes 1237","1210":"1210","ABT. 1232":"umbes 1232","1232":"1232","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Bentley, Suffolk, England":"Bentley, Suffolk, England","Bentley, Suffolk County, England":"Bentley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk Co., England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa,